These corals were selected,

23:30.090 --> 23:33.225
because one coral of the same species,

23:33.260 --> 23:35.293
sitting side-by-side,

23:35.329 --> 23:38.429
one of them was healthy and
one of them was white bleached.

23:38.465 --> 23:39.898
And our question is, "Why?"

23:39.933 --> 23:43.134
So, these are the ones that
are really the survivors.

24:08.327 --> 24:10.895
You know, I always think of
the planet as a jigsaw puzzle,

24:10.930 --> 24:14.765
and there are all these
pieces that must fit together

24:14.800 --> 24:16.533
to create the picture
that is our planet.

24:16.568 --> 24:18.869
And when you start pulling pieces out,

24:18.904 --> 24:22.005
like the coral reef
or the polar ice sheet,

24:22.040 --> 24:24.808
and that lack of
connection and understanding

24:24.843 --> 24:27.844
of the way the planet's
system is being affected

24:27.880 --> 24:30.213
will ultimately wipe
us out as a species.

24:30.248 --> 24:33.483
Species go extinct
when they can no longer

24:33.519 --> 24:36.219
be supported by the
place where they live.

24:36.254 --> 24:38.721
And that's what we're
doing to ourselves.

24:38.756 --> 24:40.489
Back in Ruth's lab,

24:40.525 --> 24:43.226
she uses a multi-million
dollar microscope

24:43.261 --> 24:44.860
which shows in stunning detail

24:44.896 --> 24:47.863
exactly how corals react
to increasing stresses.

24:47.899 --> 24:50.266
That's the first time I've seen
them where you can really see

24:50.302 --> 24:51.834
that they're living things.

24:51.869 --> 24:53.135
You're almost communicating
with the corals,

24:53.170 --> 24:56.071
'cause you can push it until
you see levels of stress...

24:56.106 --> 24:58.240
- That's right.
- ... and then pull it back in again.

24:58.275 --> 25:00.108
They tell you exactly what they feel.

25:00.144 --> 25:02.411
And that's... you know,
that's kind of crazy, isn't it?

25:02.447 --> 25:05.681
You're looking at a living organism.

25:05.716 --> 25:09.851
A reef would cross
its strongest members,

25:09.886 --> 25:13.322
naturally, over a 30- to 50-year period.

25:13.357 --> 25:15.523
We don't have 30 to 50 years.

25:15.559 --> 25:17.559
These images help Ruth experiment

25:17.594 --> 25:21.129
with ways to build stronger species.

25:21.165 --> 25:24.131
You know, originally this project
was called the Super Coral Project.

25:24.167 --> 25:25.633
Okay, I'm going out on the reef,

25:25.669 --> 25:28.235
I'm finding my best coral performers.

25:28.271 --> 25:29.637
I bring it into the lab,

25:29.673 --> 25:31.573
I train it on an environmental treadmill

25:31.608 --> 25:35.510
to improve its capacity to
withstand these temperatures.

25:35.545 --> 25:38.680
We then do what human athletes often do,

25:38.715 --> 25:41.548
which is to meet somebody in
the gym of the opposite sex

25:41.584 --> 25:44.251
and have extremely gifted offspring.

25:44.287 --> 25:46.920
And we do exactly the
same with our corals.

25:50.493 --> 25:53.160
There is an urgent, urgent problem

25:53.196 --> 25:56.663
that needs to be met with a
very, very creative solution.

25:56.699 --> 26:00.467
And I'll use an example, like,
the closure of the ozone hole.

26:00.503 --> 26:03.737
That was a radical change
in planetary behavior

26:03.772 --> 26:05.873
that enabled that to occur...

26:05.908 --> 26:07.741
and we all did it.

26:09.211 --> 26:12.379
Ruth's work is looking
like a viable solution,

26:12.414 --> 26:14.614
if it can be applied to scale.

26:14.649 --> 26:17.417
In Curacao, we met with
a team of scientists

26:17.452 --> 26:21.988
called SECORE who are trying to
solve the problem of scalability.

26:22.024 --> 26:24.891
They're here to gather the
larvae of a brain coral,

26:24.926 --> 26:28.761
their first step in a plan
to repopulate reefs worldwide.

26:56.069 --> 26:57.140
Yeah.

27:01.101 --> 27:03.294
Yeah.

27:07.935 --> 27:10.602
Once in the water, they
rely on the sea life

27:10.637 --> 27:12.537
to point them in the right direction.

27:28.788 --> 27:32.056
Once the butterfly fish have
identified the right corals,

27:32.092 --> 27:34.425
Dirk and his team cover them in tents

27:34.461 --> 27:37.761
to collect the sperm and eggs
which are about to be released.

27:56.181 --> 27:58.047
After they've collected enough samples,

27:58.083 --> 28:01.851
they need to get them back
to the lab for fertilization.

28:01.886 --> 28:04.841
In nature, the coral's
reproductive success rate

28:04.842 --> 28:06.856
is just point-two percent.

28:13.698 --> 28:17.466
It's a huge step in solving
the problem of scalability.

28:17.502 --> 28:18.801
So, how close are you to getting

28:18.837 --> 28:21.738
the potentially hundreds of
thousands of coral that are there

28:21.773 --> 28:25.108
to be hundreds of thousands
of coral in the ocean?

28:26.420 --> 28:27.843
Yeah.

28:34.652 --> 28:36.551
The next problem is how to spread

28:36.586 --> 28:38.954
these hundreds of
thousands of fertilized eggs

28:38.989 --> 28:41.523
across a wide area.

28:41.558 --> 28:45.660
These easily made cement tetrapods
are covered with coral larvae.

28:45.695 --> 28:49.764
The tetrapods can then be easily
distributed wherever they are needed,

28:49.799 --> 28:51.332
and the coral can grow.

28:51.368 --> 28:53.201
Once you've figured it out

28:53.236 --> 28:54.636
and once you know you
can do it to scale,

28:54.671 --> 28:57.104
all you have to do is get
enough of these somewhere

28:57.140 --> 29:01.876
that you can essentially push them
into the areas where they need to be.

29:01.911 --> 29:03.944
That's the idea, yeah. That's it.

29:03.980 --> 29:05.445
That's it.

29:05.481 --> 29:07.815
It's another huge step

29:07.850 --> 29:09.183
in finding a solution

29:09.218 --> 29:11.351
that can be applied
on a worldwide scale.

29:40.215 --> 29:42.248
- So, you have a blueprint.
- Yes.

29:42.283 --> 29:44.517
What would you actually
need to put that in place?

29:44.552 --> 29:46.820
- Resources. We need money.
- So, how much?

29:46.855 --> 29:50.023
A collective
hundred-million-dollar project

29:50.058 --> 29:51.824
that would create the networks,

29:51.859 --> 29:53.687
that would enable the science

29:53.688 --> 29:56.295
to be convened with
practitioners quickly.

29:57.699 --> 29:58.897
If the scale and cause

29:58.933 --> 30:01.800
of the corals' destruction
can be perfectly understood,

30:01.836 --> 30:05.338
if its most resilient species
can be selected or bred,

30:05.373 --> 30:07.340
and if those species can then be spread

30:07.375 --> 30:09.775
wherever they are needed
on a massive scale,

30:09.810 --> 30:11.777
these scientists may have solved

30:11.812 --> 30:15.180
one of the most significant
environmental problems of our age.

30:16.383 --> 30:18.016
Can you describe what
the world looks like

30:18.052 --> 30:20.919
- without coral reefs?
- A world without reefs is

30:20.955 --> 30:23.822
a world where there
are places without food,

30:23.858 --> 30:26.858
places where there's nowhere to live.

30:26.893 --> 30:32.731
They are critically important to
coastal security and economies.

30:32.766 --> 30:35.066
The rates of change in our environment

30:35.101 --> 30:38.637
are far outpacing the intrinsic capacity

30:38.672 --> 30:41.072
of coral reefs to survive.

30:41.107 --> 30:42.874
If we don't mitigate at all,

30:42.909 --> 30:45.877
coral reefs will not be the
thing that we're worrying about.

30:45.912 --> 30:48.612
It will be the survival of our species.

30:48.648 --> 30:50.414
This sounds like the perfect project

30:50.449 --> 30:51.949
crying out for someone
to come in and say,

30:51.985 --> 30:53.751
"Okay, I'm gonna
coordinate a global effort"

30:53.787 --> 30:55.286
- to do exactly what you're saying.
- Absolutely.

30:55.321 --> 31:00.123
How do we make these tools make a
difference on-site in many places?

31:00.159 --> 31:04.127
We have to be absolutely
functional in 10 years.

31:04.163 --> 31:08.799
We have to stop planning,
and we need to start doing.

